SOLUTION:

ğŸ’¾ Day 5 Lab: Creating a GP3 EBS Volume
ğŸ“– Lab Explanation
Today, we're creating an EBS (Elastic Block Store) Volume - a persistent block storage device for EC2 instances. Specifically, we're creating a GP3 volume, which is AWS's latest generation of general-purpose SSD storage.

ğŸ” Key Terms Defined
EBS (Elastic Block Store)
What: Persistent block-level storage volumes for EC2 instances

Purpose: Provides durable, network-attached storage

Persistence: Data persists independently from instance lifecycle

GP3 Volume Type
What: General Purpose SSD volume (3rd generation)

Features:

Baseline performance: 3,000 IOPS, 125 MB/s throughput

Cost-effective: Separates storage, IOPS, and throughput pricing

Modern: Successor to GP2 volumes

GiB (Gibibyte)
What: 2^30 bytes = 1,073,741,824 bytes

vs GB: GiB is binary-based, GB is decimal-based (AWS uses GiB)

ğŸš€ Benefits & Why We Use EBS Volumes
ğŸ”§ Technical Advantages
Persistence: Data remains after instance termination

Snapshots: Create point-in-time backups

Encryption: Built-in AES-256 encryption

Flexibility: Resize without downtime (with some limitations)

ğŸ’¡ GP3 Specific Benefits
Cost Savings: 20% cheaper than GP2 for same storage

Performance Control: Independent IOPS and throughput scaling

Consistent Performance: Baseline performance without bursting

ğŸ¯ Use Cases
Boot Volumes: For EC2 instance operating systems

Application Storage: Database files, application data

Data Processing: Temporary storage for data processing

Backup Storage: Target for backup and recovery

âš–ï¸ Volume Type Comparison
Type	Best For	Performance	Cost
gp3	General purpose workloads	3K-16K IOPS, 125-1000 MB/s	ğŸ’°ğŸ’°
gp2	Legacy workloads	3K-16K IOPS, 128 MB/s max	ğŸ’°ğŸ’°ğŸ’°
io1/io2	Critical databases	Up to 256K IOPS	ğŸ’°ğŸ’°ğŸ’°ğŸ’°
st1	Big data, data warehouses	500 MB/s max	ğŸ’°ğŸ’°
sc1	Cold data, archives	250 MB/s max	ğŸ’°
